Description.LocalizedString: Early concepts for their outfits evoked the brutal nature of competition in the industry.
The young singer knew the industry was cutthroat, but he had no idea just how true that could be.
Ji-Woon found the singer's range to be lacking and chose not to invite him for drinks that evening.
The socialite paraded herself before the paparazzi as she entered the club, showing off all her jewelry.
She was impeccably dressed, even if Zarina loathed everything she stood for.
She wondered what it would be like to walk in the socialite's shoes for even one day.
Kate lit a black candle etched with butterflies. She had an idea for a song about death, transformation, and transcendence.
She couldn't imagine being beloved for her tags, a countercultural icon hitting the mainstream.
She didn't choose a mainstream life. She was a rebel, and that was all she wanted to be.
The thought of selling out made her sick, but she couldn't deny that she loved the idea of wearing some designer clothing.
Felix wanted the warehouse to be more than just four walls and a roof. He wanted a story.
He stayed up late that night, trying to imagine how the people of tomorrow would live and work.
He got to work on his drafting table, drawing an innovative design featuring futuristic technology. He could breathe new life into that old building.
He watched the models strut up and down the runway, each of them staring ahead with cold, dead eyes.
He scoffed at the multi-colored jacket, but for some reason he couldn't look anywhere else.
It was a silent drive home that night, until his father asked him what he thought of the show.
Father's friends were all so attractive and refined. If he was one of them, he would have to hide his face.
Even as a child, he understood wealth of this magnitude was built on a foundation of violence and bloodshed.
A blade of shining gold, at once beautiful and brutal to behold.
She closed her eyes and tried to imagine the kinds of music that would captivate the next generation.
She wondered what daily life would look like in the future. How would people connect? What would bring them together?
She tapped her feet to the rhythm of the city's night life. Music was all around her, within and without.
She couldn't believe it. The email was an invitation to test a brand-new virtual reality gaming platform.
She was eager to give her mind and body over to a one-of-a-kind real-time immersive experience.
She lay awake in her dorm imagining how this technology could change the face of e-sports. It would be a new world to conquer.
With a hint of foreboding in her voice, she started to talk to her audience about the afterlife.
As if summoned by her words, a blue butterfly glided across the studio and landed on her microphone.
The sight of this little visitor captured Sable's imagination. She finished her show with a reminder that death is not necessarily the end.
She couldn't stand the crowd. All she could see were potential targets.
Acting on her fantasies would leave a bloody mess. It would have to wait for another night.
She styled the weapon to match her outfit, but kept it hidden in her limo.
Steroids and electric shocks were administered based on the victim's cortisol levels. More stress meant more pain.
He envisioned a system to pump adrenaline through the subject's body, keeping them conscious and energized.
The agony ended with a spark, a lone strike from an electric wand that caused the engorged muscles to tear.
She would pull out all the stops, dazzling the glitterati with her impeccable accessories.
The embellishments on her dress were a departure from her regular look, but she knew she could pull it off.
She was surprised to find herself wearing designs she had only begun to imagine once upon a time.
Those endless poker tournaments required dogged determination.
Lost in chaos, she found herself thinking of, of all people, that alluring socialite.
She couldn't remember what happened after she completed her investigation.
It was difficult to imagine walking in anyone else's shoes. All she could think about was getting out alive.
She wondered if she would ever leave another tag.
There was no rebelling in a place like this. Only the futile effort to survive.
If clothes make the person, she thought, what has this place made me?
Steroids and electric shocks were administered based on the victim's cortisol levels. Every sensation was agony.
He envisioned a system to pump adrenaline through the subject's body, to ensure his subjects were awake and aware at all moments.
The agony ended with a spark, a lone strike from an electric wand that caused tendons to rupture and skin to split open.
There was no glitterati to impress here, no one to comment on her accessories.
All the embellishments in the world couldn't change the fact that she was fighting for her life.
She wondered just how far her imagination would take her in this strange realm.
Antlers grew from the beast's head, and its piercing eyes scanned the trees for its prey.
The beast walked like a human and wore ragged clothes, an abomination of nature.
The traveler warned the crowd of the axe the beast carried. The blade glistened with the blood of victims past.
His eyes shot back and forth. He needed to prove his speed and precision against an elusive target.
His true powers were emerging from deep within. A transformation was underway.
He found his target, swung his katana, and sliced through the moth mid-flight. The night was quiet, the challenge completed.
A moth fluttered into the slaves' cage. He reached out for the creature, and it landed in his hand.
He watched as the moth crawled from his fingertips to his palm. It looked so small and weak in his grasp.
After a moment's rest, the moth was on its way again. He watched it slip out of the cage and fly freely into the night.
His character was a highly efficient assassin with a thirst for vengeance.
The leather jacket would be packed with squibs for the final shootout.
His only request was for the costume designer to add more rips to the pants.
He went on the prowl, looking to play with his next kill.
Her skin was wracked with pain, and she couldn’t understand why.
The hem of her dress smoldered with the dying remains of a once-raging fire.
The blade still glowed as if it would never lose its heat.
He dressed with caution. The cause of the darkness was beyond his understanding.
The reflective material did little to help against the evil that lurked in the dark.
Drifting ashes stuck to his gear as he ran through the darkness. It seemed to come from nowhere.
He remembered his parents giving him the sweater before his voyage. A cute little going-away present.
After her cat ruined a kite's spool during the night, Renato gave her this custom shirt as a birthday gift.
Thalita printed a custom sweater for her brother, immortalizing the time a stray dog chased his kite during a competition.
Unsure of how to dress for a college party, she turned to her coach for help.
Coach Jenny found some old jewelry at home and suggested wearing accessories to stand out.
They both agreed that a functional pair of boots and khakis would be best for the party.
It wasn't easy finding someone who understood the kind of hairstyle he wanted.
He wondered if being an outsider would work in his favor at the club.
He stood too close to the curb and got splashed when a taxi accidentally drove through a puddle.
Her grandmother spoke of people in big cities who dressed in luxury every day.
It was a family heirloom, passed down through the generations. It was meant to be hers one day.
She saw something shiny embedded in the mud before everything went black.
The fabric was threadbare in places, but still she took pleasure in wearing it.
Try as she might, Charlotte couldn't deny her sadness. The dress like this was never meant for someone like her.
Her crude instrument of self-defense stood in stark contrast to the delicate textiles.
The original piece was serviceable, but quite stark and lacking in adornment.
Applying the lavish golden details changed the piece entirely, making it something both elegant and severe.
She felt the power within the feathers, and suggested to her friend they could be used for another purpose.
Wearing the headpiece strengthened her tenuous connection to her past life.
The lavish additions took on a color all their own in this strange realm.
Looking down at her weapon conjured images of the crows that saved her life.
She knew that a week of riding would be difficult, both physically and mentally.
She could see herself accepting the massive trophy on behalf of her talented crew.
It was one of the most dangerous racing events in the world, but she knew she would be ready for it.
The local flora took its nutrients from her, just as her captors once had.
Instead of simply being sapped, she found ways to take power back. A grim symbiosis.
There was a wretched, violent beauty in the thing that she had become.
